# Cryptocurrency Price Prediction

This project investigates the prediction of next-day closing prices for five major cryptocurrencies using deep learning models implemented in PyTorch. We compare a traditional additive model (Facebook Prophet) against Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) and Gated Recurrent Unit (GRU) networks trained on different feature sets and loss functions. Specifically, we evaluate seven model configurations: Prophet as a baseline, basic LSTM and GRU using standard technical indicators, LSTM and GRU enhanced with Geometric Brownian Motion (GBM) inspired statistical features trained with MSE loss, and LSTM and GRU with GBM features trained with a custom directional penalty loss. Our results show that GBM-enhanced recurrent models consistently achieve the lowest price forecast errors, with GBM-LSTM and GBM-GRU variants reaching comparable performance. Furthermore, LSTM and GRU architectures yield near-identical results when paired with the same features and loss, suggesting that architecture choice matters far less than feature engineering. However, all models struggle to predict price direction significantly better than random chance, and the directional penalty loss does not yield a robust improvement in directional accuracy.
